title: Stable Diffusion copyright lawsuits could be a legal earthquake for AI
My ChatGPT API Bill
text:
I've been sending my git diff's to ChatGPT to generate my commit messages.

Today I checked usage from the first 2 weeks: $0.20

I originally estimated a $0.08/day (based on ~10 commits per day at ~4000 tokens per commit), but it's lower because diff's are often tiny (a few dozen characters), and I only use it for a third of my commits - the rest require thoughtful (human) messages.

In any case, this was a fun experiment, and a cheap way to save, I dunno, 5 minutes a week :)

Usage/cost graph: https://imgur.com/a/X7Ldqq1

Initial cost estimate: https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=35303100

Source code: https://github.com/stevecondylios/gpt-generated-commit-messages#setup

Show HN: Aicombinator – Bot to automate tasks across browser and APIs
text:
This tool uses GPT-3.5-Turbo to generate code that invokes recipes which are either puppeteer-based or use activepieces to invoke API actions for many popular sites and apps.

Ability to use a local browser enables the bot to fill in OTPs (SMS/Email/2FA etc), fill forms and make payments etc. Ability to use ActivePieces brings support for OAuth-based connections. Puppeteer recipes are currently human-written and human-reviewed but these could be automated in the future.

This is barely working as I built it for a hackathon this weekend. Open-sourcing it in the hope of faster improvements.

Show HN: I build a Native Windows client for ChatGPT
text:
Greetings!
I just released EasyChat - A native Windows client for using ChatGPT.
It is designed with the latest Windows 11 UI design principles, using WinUI3, Mica, and Fluent design.
Some features:
* Chat history
* Streaming support
* API Key and chat history is saved locally
Planned features:
* Search
* Chat Pinning
* Model Selection
The app does not communicate to anything except OpenAI and Microsoft AppCenter/Store.
To get as much feedback as possible, the unlimited version can be purchased for free within the app for the next 48 hours. It is a kind of MVP. But we are eager to improve it further.
I’d love for you to try it out and your thoughts and insights!

Ask HN: What's the state of mobile app monetization in 2023?
text:
Hey HN - I'm a co-owner of a mobile app (Android and iOS) for a specific niche with a substantial user base (B2C). We've tried for a couple of years to build an innovative business model on top of it, but it turned out to be unsustainable and we want to restructure to a more traditional app business model.

The landscape seems to have changed quite a bit in the last few years with the crackdown on ad tracking on iOS, more subscriptions, etc. Blogs on this topic seem to be at least a few years old or SaaS marketing content.

What's the current state of mobile app monetization? Are any of one-time purchases, subscriptions, ads, paid sponsorships for our industry, … still viable for an app with on-going development of new features?
